observations.recommendation:
We recommended and Management agreed to the following:
The Accounting Office, in coordination with the General Service Office, expedite the identification of those unreconciled PPEs and same be prepared/maintained with respective PPELCs to ensure that balances of PPEs appearing on the financial statements are duly supported and substantiated;
The Appraisal and Inventory Committee conduct physical count of all PPEs including Land Improvements, Infrastructure Assets, Buildings and Other Structures and other PPEs owned by the municipality; and ensure that RPCPPE is prepared and signed in accordance with the requirement prescribed in Volume II of the Manual on the NGAS for LGUs;
The Municipal Engineer, as the AO for the lost drone, submit request for relief from accountability to this Office duly supported with his justification for failure to immediately notify the Auditor after the discovery of such loss, as well as the required documents stipulated in Section 151 and 152 of COA Circular No. 92-386 dated October 20, 1992 such as: blotter report, affidavits, and progress/final investigation report of the head of the agency and proper government investigating agency, among others;
Avail the one-time cleansing of PPE accounts by following the guidelines and procedures set forth in COA Circular No. 2020-006 dated January 31, 2020. To ensure implementation thereto, create a team or committee who shall focus on the proper execution of the aforementioned circular with a concrete timeline; and
The Municipal Accountant effect the reclassification of semi-expendable properties below the capitalization threshold of ₱50,000.00 to their appropriate expense accounts and record the cumulative effect of change in accounting policy using Prior Period Adjustment account as prescribed under Circular No. 2022-004 dated May 31, 2022.

We recommended and Management agreed to the following:
The Municipal Accountant record in the books reconciling items that were identified and were found valid during the preparation of bank reconciliation;
For those which are yet to be determined, the Municipal Treasurer and Municipal Accountant exert efforts to reconcile/trace/locate missing documents and records to ensure that the reconciling items presented in the BRS are correctly valid and can be taken up in the books;
The Municipal Accountant ensure preparation of BRS for all bank accounts of the Municipality on a monthly basis as well as the year-end BRS for timely reconciliation and corrections/adjustment of any discrepancies/errors, as well as, timely submission of the same to the Auditor;
Prepare Sangguiang Bayan Resolution reactivating those dormant accounts under Trust Fund, and the Municipal Accountant and Treasurer reevaluate its purpose and corresponding balances if the same accrues to the municipality or to the source agency for its proper disposition;
The Municipal Treasurer notify payees of those checks that has become stale for its cancellation and replacement and ensure that cancelled checks are then reported in the RCI;
For stale checks which are still unclaimed, the Municipal Treasurer forward the original DV and supporting documents to the Municipal Accountant for appropriate adjustments in the books and ensure that cancelled checks are then reported in the RCI;
The Municipal Accountant draw Journal Entry Voucher to effect the necessary adjustments in the cancellation of checks issued. For long outstanding stale checks for which presentation of the actual checks is no longer feasible despite notifying the concerned payees, the Municipal Accountant make the appropriate adjustments based on the details indicated in the RCI and BRS;
The Municipal Treasurer and Municipal Accountant reconcile the noted difference ₱13.289 million and effect the necessary and applicable adjustments/corrections in their respective records;
The Municipal Treasurer update and balance daily its cashbooks, and at the end of the month rule and foot the same in order to reflect the month-end balances per account;
The Municipal Accountant, in coordination with the Municipal Treasurer, include in the preparation of the BRS the reconciliation of Cash in Bank-LCCA balance per cashbook and ensure that the balances presented in the BRS are consistent with the cashbooks maintained; and
Henceforth, the Municipal Treasurer and Municipal Accountant ensure periodic and timely reconciliation between their records so that errors or any other reconciling items will be immediately corrected/updated.

We recommended and Management agreed to the following:
The Municipal Accountant exert more effort in identifying those unreconciled balances by determining its nature, purpose, amount and the source agency. Thereafter, maintain SLs per fund source as support to those balances that were identified under the Due to NGAs account;
Evaluate whether projects thereof have been implemented, find its Memorandum of Agreement (MOA)/and or coordinate with the SA to determine the disposition of the fund. Otherwise, revert the fund/unutilized balance to the SA in accordance with existing rules and regulations;
The Municipal Treasurer, in coordination with the Municipal Accountant, revert to the SA unutilized funds of completed projects pursuant to Section 6.7 of COA Circular No. 94-013;
The Municipal Accountant make appropriate adjusting journal entry in the Trust Fund by debiting “Due to PhilHealth” account and crediting “Due to NGAs” account amounting to ₱2.940 million to correct the erroneous entry noted;
The Municipal Treasurer trace back all prior years’ collections from building permit fees and other charges in order to compute for the five percent DPWH share and remit the same to the BTr;
The Municipal Accountant henceforth, recognized in the books the five percent DPWH share by crediting “Due to NGAs” account in the GF book upon collection and debit the same upon remittance.

We recommended and Management agreed to the following:
Trace up and reconcile the details of the unidentified receivable accounts of ₱452,074.97 and effect the necessary correcting/adjusting entries;
Exhaust all possible remedies in collecting the overdue accounts;
Analyze the accounts and recognize impairment of receivables where recovery has ceased to be probable, to ensure reasonable presentation of account balances in the financial statements; and
Request authority from COA to write-off from the books, those accounts which qualify for derecognition pursuant to COA Circular No. 2023-008.

We recommended and Management agreed to the following:
The GSO include in the RPCPPE all unserviceable items found during the physical count and for those with no records, indicate in the report the general description of the item for its identity;
The GSO prepare the IIRUP and conduct immediate disposal of all unserviceable properties through its disposal committee in accordance with Section 79 of PD 1445, to prevent further deterioration and loss of additional income;
The GSO update the IIRUP after disposal of unserviceable properties and furnish a copy thereof to the Municipal Accountant and Audit Team; and
The Municipal Accountant draw a journal entry voucher to derecognize/drop from the books of accounts the disposed unserviceable properties based on the IIRUP submitted by the GSO.

The Municipal Planning and Development Coordinator (MPDC) provide explanation as to non-inclusion of function hall and honoraria of RPs in the program design;

The facilitators of the UHC Orientation provide pictures as proof that it was actually conducted and provide copy of the Course/Topical Outline and names of the designated RPs for validation. Likewise, submit explanation/ justification for our re-evaluation/validation as to the following:

The 31 participants per signed attendance sheets that were not among the plantilla or job order health workers of the municipality;

The noted two persons with paid boat tickets that were not among the attendees; and

The 21 participants reflected in the signed attendance sheets but not supported with boat tickets as proof of travelling to and from Boracay on the dates of the Orientation.

The Municipal Accountant (MA) provide explanation on the noted discrepancy of ₱5.246 million between the BRS and SLs balances and effect the necessary adjustments/corrections and ensure that the balances presented in the BRS are consistent with the SLs maintained to establish the existence, accuracy and reliability of the Cash in Bank-LCCA balance presented in the financial statements;

The MA review and analyze those long outstanding book reconciling items and, if found valid, cause the preparation of necessary adjusting journal entries; and

Henceforth, conduct a regular reconciliation of their balances so that the adjustments made or errors detected either by the Treasury or Accounting Office will be timely adjusted and posted in their respective books.

The MT to regularly update the Real Property Tax Account Register (RPTAR) or Taxpayer’s Index Card which shall serve as the basis in the preparation of the List of Delinquent Real Property Tax Payers as of the end of the year, the total of which shall equal the RPT/SET Receivable at year-end; and to prepare a duly certified list showing the name of the taxpayers and the amount due and collectible, and submit the same to the MA to serve as the basis in setting up the beginning balance of RPT/SET Receivable in the books of accounts. In such manner, the related receivable account and deferred liability will be presented fairly in the financial statements;

The MA and MT to conduct reconciliation of records based on the index card balances so that necessary adjustments could be made to bring the affected receivable and deferred accounts to its correct balance; and

The MA to prepare and maintain SLs for RPT/SET Receivables based on the certified list of taxpayers and its corresponding amount due and collectibles from the MT.

We recommended and the Management agreed to the following:
The Municipal Treasurer and Municipal Accountant immediately reconcile their records/books to determine the necessary corrections from the unreconciled difference of ₱14.693 million between SLs and CBs;
The Municipal Treasurer update and balance daily its cashbooks, and at the end of the month rule and foot the same in order to reflect the month-end balances per account, and regularly reconcile with the monthly balances per bank and per book;
The Municipal Accountant, in coordination with the Municipal Treasurer, include in the preparation of the BRS the reconciliation of “Cash in Bank-LCCA” balance per cashbook and ensure that the balances presented in the BRS are consistent with the subsidiary ledgers/cashbooks maintained; and
The Municipal Accountant ensure submission of BRS for all bank accounts of the Municipality on a monthly basis as well as the year-end BRS for timely reconciliation and corrections/adjustment of any discrepancies/errors and to reflect the correct balance of the accounts in the financial statements.

The MA expedite the identification of unreconciled balances of “Due to NGAs” and “Due to LGUs” account and maintain the corresponding SLs thereof per fund source;

The Municipal Social Worker and Development Office (MSWDO) provide sufficient evidence/ supporting documents to establish that the recipients of the financial assistance distributed are actually the victims/affected individuals of Typhoon Odette and that the amount released to them equates to the number of family members affected;

The MSWDO submit explanation/ justification on the inconsistencies noted in Appendix E and provide sufficient evidence/ supporting documents to establish that the recipients of the financial assistance distributed are indeed residents of the said barangay as indicated in its corresponding payroll; 

The MSWDO conduct henceforth, a thorough assessment/ evaluation to beneficiaries of any financial assistance and same be sufficiently documented to guarantee responsive, equitable and effective distribution thereof and prevent any misuse of funds;

The Municipal Planning and Development Coordinator (MPDC) provide explanation as to non-inclusion of function hall and honoraria of RPs in the program design;

The facilitators of the UHC Orientation provide pictures as proof that it was actually conducted and provide copy of the Course/Topical Outline and names of the designated RPs for validation. Likewise, submit explanation/ justification for our re-evaluation/validation as to the following:

The 31 participants per signed attendance sheets that were not among the plantilla or job order health workers of the municipality;

The noted two persons with paid boat tickets that were not among the attendees; and

The 21 participants reflected in the signed attendance sheets but not supported with boat tickets as proof of travelling to and from Boracay on the dates of the Orientation.

The Municipal Treasurer (MT) ensure henceforth, that liquidation of cash advances for payroll were supported by Report of Disbursements that will serve as basis by the MA in preparing the appropriate journal entries; and

The MA ensure henceforth, that all disbursements particularly in the seminar/trainings/orientations conducted by the municipality are supported with Office Order, Course Outline, Certified and Validated Attendance Sheets and all other supporting documents relevant and sufficient thereto.

The Supply Officer ensure that pictures are taken and properly labelled for each procurement and ensure that the same can be identified and quantified with the items procured based on the PO;

The MSWDO ensure that RDSs are completely filled out and signed by authorized personnel/official;

Ensure that Office Order are prepared for trainings/seminars conducted by Municipality to its personnel as this will serve as their authority to attend trainings/seminars and basis in preparing the PR; 

The MA ensure that disbursements are properly supported with complete documentation and provided with adequate information to  establish that the transactions/activities transpired, and discontinue the practice of processing payment for claims that are not sufficiently documented to avoid issuance of Notice of Suspensions or Disallowances; and

The BAC: a) conduct due diligence in recommending and determining the mode of procurement; b) adhere with the provisions of RA 9184 in all its procurement activities; and c) ensure that the most advantageous price to the Municipality is obtained.

The Municipal Development Council re-evaluate the PPAs under continuing appropriations and cause the reversion or re-alignment of the appropriated funds for PPAs no longer needed or necessary so that same may be used effectively and efficiently for more appropriate priority development projects;

Revert the unutilized balances of appropriations classified as MOOE to the general fund so that same may be used in the next budget preparation and be appropriated for other projects of the Municipality; and

The MPDC and Municipal Engineer regularly monitor all the programs and projects of the municipality and submit a monitoring report as basis to issue memorandum to the implementing office to ensure full implementation of the development projects.

The Accounting Office in coordination with the GSO exert more effort in identifying/reconciling those PPEs acquired before CY 2016 so that the same will be included in the PPELCs maintained by the Accounting Office and direct the Municipal Accountant to ensure that balances of PPEs appearing on the financial statements are supported and reconciled with the balances reflected in the PPELC;
The Appraisal and Inventory Committee conduct the physical count of PPEs including other PPEs like Other Land Improvements, Infrastructure Assets and Other Buildings and Other Structures, and present the same in the RPCPPE;
The Appraisal and Inventory Committee determine the appraised value of donated properties and those unserviceable properties found on station so that these properties can be correctly recorded/adjusted in the books of accounts of the municipality;
The GSO and the Accounting Office conduct reconciliation of their PPE records (PC and PPELC) to ascertain the discrepancy and to make the necessary adjustments in order to establish the completeness, accuracy and existence of the PPE accounts presented in the Financial Statements; and
The Appraisal and Inventory Committee properly prepare and submit the RPCPPE to facilitate smooth identification and verification of properties and its balances.

The Municipal Treasurer and Municipal Accountant reconcile immediately their records/books to determine the necessary corrections from the unreconciled difference of ₱18.680 million;
Henceforth, conduct a regular reconciliation of their balances so that the adjustments made or errors detected either by the Treasury or Accounting Office will be timely adjusted and posted in their respective books;
The Municipal Accountant review and analyze those long outstanding book reconciling items and, if found valid, cause the preparation of necessary adjusting journal entries; and
The Municipal Accountant and Municipal Treasurer verify and review outstanding checks which have become stale, and require the latter to cancel the unclaimed stale checks and furnish the Municipal Accountant copy of the Disbursement Vouchers for the preparation of the corresponding journal entries.

The Municipal Accountant in coordination with the Supply Officer trace back all inventories already issued based on the RIS and stock card maintained by the General Services Office, and make the appropriate adjusting entries to properly account the same in the books of the Municipality;
The Appraisal and Inventory Committee conduct semestral physical count of inventory items in the custody of the Supply Officer to determine undistributed/unconsumed items, if any; and
The Supply Officer prepare SSMI summarizing all issued inventories as basis by the Accounting Office in preparing Journal Entry Voucher.

Re-evaluate the PPAs under continuing appropriations and cause the reversion or re-alignment of the appropriated funds for PPAs no longer needed or necessary so that same may be used effectively and efficiently for more appropriate priority development projects;
Ensure that the development projects funded under the 20% Development Fund comply with the guidelines set forth in the DBM-DOF-DILG JMC 2020-1 dated November 4, 2020 and optimally contribute to the attainment of desirable socio-economic targets and outcomes of the Municipality; and
Revert the unutilized balances of the appropriations classified as MOOE to the general fund so that funds may be used in the next budget preparation and can be appropriated for other priority projects of the Municipality.

We recommended and the management agreed to the following:

Submit duly certified and corrected Summary of Disbursements together with the signed payroll and supporting documents of the nine unreconciled and unsupported beneficiaries;

The Municipal Treasurer and MSWDO provide the complete set of documents indicated in the “Remarks’ column of Appendix D such as photocopy of ID, and specimen signatures as supporting documents to certain beneficiaries in the payroll;

In consideration with the vast numbers of beneficiaries, require the MSWDO to provide electronic copy of photos with names of each beneficiary per barangay saved in a compact disk (CD) in lieu of print outs; and

Provide explanation/ justification for the non-execution of MOA between LGU and MSWD on the implementation of the ESP thru SAP and require the concerned DSWD official to provide duly signed certification attesting the management’s assertion that the unutilized balance of ₱96,0000 was authorized to be distributed to other beneficiaries.

We recommended and the management agreed to the following:

The LDRRMO provide/indicate the projects and activities charged to the unexpended LDRRMF of previous years in preparing the LDRRMFIP;

Ensure the timely submission by the LDRRMO and Municipal Accountant of the monthly Report on Utilization of Disaster Risk Reduction and Management Fund on or before 15th day after the end of each month;

The Municipal Accountant and Budget Officer prepare the monthly Report on the Receipt and Utilization of DRRM Sourced from GAA and ensure its timely submission on the 5th day following the end 
of each month to the concerned offices; and

The Municipal Accountant prepare and maintain subsidiary ledgers for each type of Disaster Response and Rescue Equipment.

We recommended to the Local Chief Executive the following:

Require the Municipal Accountant to compute the correct depreciation expenses of its assets and a journal entry must be drawn to update/correct the accumulated depreciation by a debit to depreciation expense (for the current year depreciation), debit to prior year’s adjustment (for the prior year’s depreciation) and a credit to accumulated depreciation (for the total unrecorded depreciation);

Exert effort through the General Services Office/Office of the Municipal Treasurer, to reconstruct and update its property records and reconcile with the accounting records to facilitate the setting up and periodic provision of depreciation for those depreciable assets not provided with depreciation;
Create an appraisal committee to conduct evaluation of assets whose records could not be found in order to establish the commencement of depreciation of the subjected assets and determine their depreciable cost and estimated remaining life for the computation of their respective depreciation; and

Henceforth, the Municipal Accountant see to it that all depreciable properties owned by the LGU are provided with depreciation in accordance with the above-mentioned rules and regulations to ensure its fair presentation in the financial statements.

We recommended to the Local Chief Executive the following:
The Municipal Treasurer to regularly update the Real Property Tax Account Register (RPTAR) or Taxpayer’s Index Card which shall serve as the basis in the preparation of the List of Delinquent Real Property Tax Payers as of the end of the year, the total of which shall equal the RPT/SET Receivable at year-end; and to prepare a duly certified list showing the name of the taxpayers and the amount due and collectible, and submit the same to the Municipal Accountant to serve as the basis in setting up the beginning balance of RPT/SET Receivable in the books of accounts. In such manner, the related receivable account and deferred liability will be presented fairly in the financial statements;
The Municipal Accountant and Treasurer to conduct reconciliation of  records based on the index card balances  so that necessary adjustments could be made to bring the affected receivable and deferred accounts to its correct balance;
The Municipal Accountant to prepare and maintain subsidiary ledgers for RPT/SET Receivables based on the certified list of taxpayers and its corresponding amount due and collectibles from the Municipal Treasurer; and
The Local Chief Executive (LCE), Municipal Treasurer and other concerned Municipal Officials to exert concerted efforts to intensify collections of long outstanding RPT and SET Receivables including the interest thereon so that more development programs may be implemented for the benefit of the constituents.

Require the contractor to pay the unaccomplished work and impose the uncessary liquidated damages from the delay/non completion of the project in accordance with the program of works without prejudice to other courses of action and remedies available under the circumstances;
Find ways on how to utilize and maximize the constructed/rehabilitated Public Market so as not to put government funds and properties in vain;
Take note of the other deficiencies noted and make the necessary action to address the same and prevent further maintenance cost by the municipality; and
The Municipal Engineer and/or personnel in-charge of government projects to be reminded of their responsibility/accountability to ensure that the projects turned-over by the contractor was inspected in accordance with the Program of Works and its related contract to ensure that the same was completed accordingly before acceptance.

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive require the Municipal Treasurer and Collecting Officers to strictly observe the following suggested measures:

1.	Deposit all collections intact with the authorized depository bank (AGDB) daily or not later than the next banking day;

2.	The Collecting Officers to remit daily and intact their collections to the Municipal Treasurer and the same should be duly acknowledge by the latter by signifying her signature in the Verification and Acknowledgement section of the RCD; 

3.	The RCDs to be duly numbered as a means of control and reference;

4.	Stop immediately the practice of holding large amount of undeposited/unremitted collections as proper safeguard of government funds; and 

5.	Install proper measure/control that would ensure proper safeguard and monitoring of the collections and remittances/deposits transaction of the Municipality.

We recommended the following:

Prioritize the implementation of the recommendations of DENR-EMB Region VI on the immediate rehabilitation and closure of the Municipal Disposal Site; 

Adapt an Alternative Technology that shall process collected residual waste into a resource or new products/materials such as hollow blocks, eco-bricks, planks or aggregate to construction materials to avoid congestion of unprocessed residual wastes in the facility;

Continually look for suitable site for a sanitary landfill that will be developed and operated as a final disposal site for solid and, eventually, residual wastes of the municipality in compliance with the Solid Waste Management Act;

Materials Recovery Facility be established in every barangay or cluster of barangays.  The municipality may initially pilot a single barangay to establish MRF project in order to institute a system of knowledge in establishing one as well as to gain commitment/participation of barangay officials on the proper administration and the operation of MRF; and

Intensify the Information, Education and Communication campaign to its stakeholders on waste reduction and proper waste segregation and strictly impose and enforce the fines and penalties for violators.

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive require the Municipal Treasurer and Collecting Officers to strictly observe the following suggested measures:
1.	Deposit all collections intact with the authorized depository bank (AGDB) daily or not later than the next banking day;
2.	The Collecting Officers to remit daily and intact their collections to the Municipal Treasurer and the same should be duly acknowledge by the latter by signifying her signature in the Verification and Acknowledgement section of the RCD;
3.	The RCDs to be duly numbered as a means of control and reference;
4.	Stop immediately the practice of holding large amount of undeposited/unremitted collections as proper safeguard of government funds;
5.	Install proper measure/control that would ensure proper safeguard and monitoring of the collections and remittances/deposits transaction of the Municipality; and
6.	Failing to comply after three written reminders to the accountable officer concerned, file an appropriate administrative case against the said accountable officer.

We recommended the following:
Prioritize the implementation of the recommendations of DENR-EMB Region VI on the immediate rehabilitation and closure of the Municipal Disposal Site;
Adapt an Alternative Technology that shall process collected residual waste into a resource or new products/materials such as hollow blocks, eco-bricks, planks or aggregate to construction materials to avoid congestion of unprocessed residual wastes in the facility;
Continually look for suitable site for a sanitary landfill that will be developed and operated as a final disposal site for solid and, eventually, residual wastes of the municipality in compliance with the Solid Waste Management Act;
Materials Recovery Facility be established in every barangay or cluster of barangays.  The municipality may initially pilot a single barangay to establish MRF project in order to institute a system of knowledge in establishing one as well as to gain commitment/participation of barangay officials on the proper administration and the operation of MRF; and
Intensify the Information, Education and Communication campaign to its stakeholders on waste reduction and proper waste segregation and strictly impose and enforce the fines and penalties for violators.

We recommend that: 
a.The Local Chief Executive requires the Municipal Accountant to follow strictly the provision of Section 271 (d) of R.A. 7160.  The Municipal Accountant should exert effort to prepare the disbursement voucher for the release of said shares on a quarterly basis, meantime that there is lack of personnel;

b.The Municipal Accountant requests for an additional personnel who will be tasked on the monitoring and preparation of the vouchers for barangay shares.

Demand from the AO with outstanding cash advances as of December 31, 2016 the immediate liquidation of such cash advances with the provision that if not liquidated within 30 days upon receipt of the demand letter, the same shall be deducted from their salaries;
Require the Municipal Accountant to certify on the face of the voucher for cash advances that the AO has no previous outstanding or unliquidated cash advances;
Require the Municipal Accountant to maintain subsidiary ledger for each AO with cash advances complete with details: purpose, date granted, Check No., date of check, JEV No. date of liquidation etc. to ensure proper monitoring of the liquidation on cash advances granted as required by existing regulation.
